.TH "dma_pool_alloc" 9 "dma_pool_alloc" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
dma_pool_alloc \- get a block of consistent memory
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "void *" dma_pool_alloc
.BI "(struct dma_pool *pool "  ","
.BI "gfp_t mem_flags "  ","
.BI "dma_addr_t *handle "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "pool" 12
dma pool that will produce the block
.IP "mem_flags" 12
GFP_* bitmask
.IP "handle" 12
pointer to dma address of block
.SH "RETURN"
the kernel virtual address of a currently unused block,
and reports its dma address through the handle.
If such a memory block can't be allocated, NULL is returned.
